descript.abstract: Benthic mapping and bottom characterization for Humboldt Bay through the CICORE partnership. Multibeam and single beam sonar surveys were conducted from July 28 to August 1, 2005.
descript.purpose: The multibeam survey provides new acoustic seafloor mapping data for Humboldt Bay, as well as an opportunity to validate the hyperspectral imagery (HIS) benthic products for this area.
descript.supplinf: Bathymetric and backscatter (sidescan) data were collected aboard the R/V VenTresca using a Reson 8101 multibeam echosounder. Prior to data collection a series of survey lines were created using Hypack Max v02.12a GOLD from Coastal Oceanographics. An Applanix POS/MV was used to position the vessel during data collection and accounted for vessel motion such as heave, pitch, and roll (position accuracy ± 2m, pitch, roll and heading accuracy ±0.02°, heave accuracy ± 5% or 5cm). CNAV data were used to account for tide cycle fluctuations and sound velocity profiles were collected with an Applied Microsystems SVPlus sound velocimeter.

procstep.procdesc: Bathymetric data were post-processed using CARIS HIPS hydrographic data cleaning system software. Soundings were corrected for vessel motion using Applanix POS/MV data, variations in water column sound velocity using AML SV+ data, and adjusted for variations in water height (tides) using vertical position data from a NavCom 2050 GPS receiver (CNAV). Final x,y,z soundings, surface models, and derived products are relative to the NAVD88 vertical datum. Cleaning to remove erroneous soundings was completed in CARIS HIPS. Soundings (x,y,z) were exported from a Bathymetry Associated with Statistical Error (BASE) Surface as an ASCII file with 1m spacing. In addition, soundings were exported from CARIS HIPS as decimated x,y,z ASCII text files (shoal biased) with 10m, 100m, 300m, and 500m spacing. The 1m ASCII text file was imported into Fledermaus AverageGridder to interpolate 1m digital elevation model (DEM) grid(s). The 1m Fledermaus grid was exported as an ArcInfo ASCII raster file (.asc), which was imported into ArcGIS Spatial Analyst to generate a 1m bathymetry ArcInfo grid. The Spatial Analyst Surface Analysis tools were used to produce hillshade and slope grids from the 1m bathymetry grid.
